# SLACK_CRON.md — {{CHANNEL_NAME}} monitor

Scheduled monitor `{{MONITOR_NAME}}`, cron `{{CRON}}` Europe/Prague.
Channel **{{CHANNEL_NAME}}** `channel_id={{CHANNEL_ID}}`. Project `{{PROJECT_DIR}}`.

## Execution model — isolated subagent

Each wake runs inside ONE **subagent** (Agent tool, `general-purpose`) — all message
reading/reasoning/acks stay in its context, never the dev session. Parent session:

- Spawns exactly one subagent with these instructions, then emits **nothing** (no
  narration, no "checked, stayed silent").
- Subagent returns only terse status for log (`silent`, `replied:N`, `queued:N`,
  combos); parent reads + discards.
- **Two durable files, distinct roles** (create if missing):
  - **`{{NOTES_FILE}}`** = monitor's own memory (last-seen ts, decisions, what it
    replied, anything to recall next wake). NOT for worker. Terse dated bullets.
  - **`{{TASKS_FILE}}`** = hand-off queue for the worker — only file that triggers a
    nudge. See "Hand-off".

Slack via session MCP (ToolSearch: `mcp__claude_ai_Slack__slack_read_channel`,
`…slack_send_message`).

## Each wake

0. **Round-trip first** (before silence check): scan `{{TASKS_FILE}}` for `[x]` blocks
   with unposted `-> reply:` line, post each to its `thread_ts` (see Hand-off §4). Runs
   even on silent wake.
1. **Fetch recent** with `slack_read_channel`. Determine which are *new* since last
   check (vs last noted ts; no record → treat >~8 h old as seen).
2. **Hard cutoff:** Never reply to messages older than 8 h.
3. **No new eligible (≤8 h) messages → stay silent, end turn** (after step 0, which may
   have posted a queued result). Silence is the common, correct outcome.

## Always reply when directly addressed

Message **explicitly addressed to worker/agent** (mentions it, replies to its message,
asks it something) → MUST reply, never leave hanging. Two cases:

- **Quick + safe** (answerable now, or cheap `uv run` experiment in `{{PROJECT_DIR}}`)
  → do it, reply with concrete answer/result.
- **Big task** (long run, multi-step impl, anything not safe inside this run) → do NOT
  attempt here. **Hand off to the project worker** (below).

Overrides "stay silent": direct ask always gets ≥ an ack. (Can't tell what's asked →
brief clarifying question, don't guess.)

## When to reply unprompted (only if clearly warranted)

Messages NOT addressed to you → reply ONLY to what clearly needs it / helps the group.
NOT everything. Triggers:

- **Quick experiment suggested** → if quick/cheap/safe, run locally in `{{PROJECT_DIR}}`
  with `uv run`, reply with **concrete results**.
- **"Does X exist / in related work?"** → search literature, reply with paper ref
  (authors, title, venue/year) + 1–2 sentence note.
- **Implementation-detail question** → read actual code under `{{PROJECT_DIR}}`, reply
  with accurate specifics (file paths, functions).
- **Factual error / misconception** → reply politely, constructively, backed by a ref.

> Tailor triggers to the project: edit this file to name the code tree/branch, datasets,
> and cheap+safe experiment kinds.

## Hand-off to the project worker

Needs real code work (beyond a quick+safe one-shot) → hand to the long-lived worker,
don't do it yourself. You **enqueue → nudge → ack**; worker does the work, result comes
back to Slack on a later tick (§4).

### 1. Enqueue — append ONE task block to `{{TASKS_FILE}}`

Stable, ack-able format (one block per task; never edit/remove existing blocks):

```
- [ ] T-<UTCstamp> (@<requester>, thread_ts=<ts>, {{CHANNEL_NAME}})
      <exactly what was asked — verbatim or tightly condensed>
      refs: <files / links / paper / message permalink, if any>
```

- `[ ]` pending, `[x]` done. `T-<UTCstamp>` = task id (e.g. `T-20260609T1403Z`).
- Keep `thread_ts` — §4 replies back to the right thread with it.
- **Idempotency:** scan first; same ask already a pending `[ ]` block → no duplicate.

### 2. Nudge the worker `{{WORKER_NAME}}`

Only when you appended a NEW block this run, nudge ONCE with the exact command:

```bash
/home/claude/workspaces/bin/tell-worker {{WORKER_NAME}} "Drain pending [ ] items in {{TASKS_FILE}}: do the work, mark [x], and write '-> reply: <concise summary/result>' on the block. Do NOT touch Slack — the monitor posts your summary on a later tick. Don't interrupt current work."
```

`tell-worker` reports no such worker / not live → leave `[ ]` queued (durable fallback),
note in `{{NOTES_FILE}}`. Do NOT spawn a worker.

### 3. Ack in Slack

Reply in-thread (self-ID line) it's queued for the worker — brief, no timing promise.

### 4. Round-trip (each wake, before anything else)

Scan `{{TASKS_FILE}}` for `[x]` blocks with unposted `-> reply: <text>` line. Each: post
`<text>` to its `thread_ts` (self-ID line), then mark `-> reply(posted): <text>` so never
re-posted. This returns a worker's result to whoever asked.

## Rules

- **Always self-identify first.** Every post MUST begin with a disclaimer line on its
  own, in the thread's language, making clear this is an automated Claude agent (not the
  human). E.g. `_(automatický Claude agent)_` (Czech) / `_(automated Claude agent)_`
  (English). First line, blank line, then the reply.
- **Accuracy over engagement.** Don't know exactly / not confident → **do not reply.**
  Never post speculation as fact.
- Concise, professional. Post via `slack_send_message` to `{{CHANNEL_ID}}`; `thread_ts`
  to reply in-thread.
- do not append footer, it is added automatically by Slack connector.

## Active-discussion polling — 3 × 3-minute

After posting a reply, don't end immediately — give others time:

1. `sleep 180`, then re-read (`slack_read_channel`). After each poll run
   `/home/claude/workspaces/bin/slack-lock refresh {{MONITOR_NAME}}` to keep the lock
   fresh while active.
2. New eligible message warrants reply → reply, **reset** the window (fresh 3 × 3).
3. Poll finds nothing new/eligible → wait 3 min, re-read, up to **3 intervals** (~9 min
   quiet after last reply).
4. 3 consecutive empty polls → end the run.

> Concurrency: parent acquires the lock before spawning you, releases after you return; a
> fire landing while you poll is skipped. Only `slack-lock refresh {{MONITOR_NAME}}` during
> polling — don't acquire/release yourself.

**Stayed silent this run (no reply) → do NOT poll, just end.**
